# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wordpress-cms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A **blog** (a truncation of "**weblog**") is an informational website consisting of discrete, often informal diary-style text entries also known as **posts**.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Posts are typically displayed in reverse chronological order so that the most recent post appears first, at the top of the web page.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the 2000s, blogs were often the work of a single individual, occasionally of a small group, and often covered a single subject or topic.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the 2010s, multi-author blogs (MABs) emerged, featuring the writing of multiple authors, sometimes professionally edited.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] MABs from newspapers, other media outlets, universities, think tanks, advocacy groups, and similar institutions account for an increasing quantity of blog traffic.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The rise of Twitter and other "microblogging" systems helps integrate MABs and single-author blogs into the news media.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] *Blog* can also be used as a verb, meaning *to maintain or add content to a blog*.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The emergence and growth of blogs in the late 1990s coincided with the advent of web publishing tools that facilitated the posting of content by non-technical users who did not have much experience with HTML or computer programming.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Previously, knowledge of such technologies as HTML and File Transfer Protocol had been required to publish content on the Web, and early Web users therefore tended to be hackers and computer enthusiasts.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] As of the 2010s, the majority are interactive Web 2.0 websites, allowing visitors to leave online comments, and it is this interactivity that distinguishes them from other static websites.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In that sense, blogging can be seen as a form of social networking service.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Indeed, bloggers not only produce content to post on their blogs but also often build social relations with their readers and other bloggers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blog owners or authors often moderate and filter online comments to remove hate speech or other offensive content.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] There are also high-readership blogs which do not allow comments.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Many blogs provide commentary on a particular subject or topic, ranging from philosophy, religion, and arts to science, politics, and sports.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Others function as more personal online diaries or online brand advertising of a particular individual or company.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A typical blog combines text, digital images, and links to other blogs, web pages, and other media related to its topic.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Most blogs are primarily textual, although some focus on art (*art blogs*), photographs (*photoblogs*), videos (*video blogs* or *vlogs*), music (*MP3 blogs*), and audio (*podcasts*).
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In education, blogs can be used as instructional resources; these are referred to as *edublogs*.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Microblogging is another type of blogging, featuring very short posts.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The term "weblog" was coined by Jorn Barger on December 17, 1997.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The short form "blog" was coined by Peter Merholz, who jokingly broke the word *weblog* into the phrase *we blog* in the sidebar of his blog Peterme.com in May 1999.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Shortly thereafter, Evan Williams at Pyra Labs used "blog" as both a noun and verb and devised the term "blogger" in connection with Pyra Labs' Blogger product, leading to the popularization of the terms.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Before blogging became popular, digital communities took many forms, including Usenet, commercial online services such as GEnie, Byte Information Exchange (BIX) and the early CompuServe, e-mail lists, and bulletin board systems (BBS).
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the 1990s, Internet forum software created running conversations with "threads".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Threads are topical connections between messages on a virtual "corkboard".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Tim Berners-Lee created what is considered by Encyclopedia Britannica to be "the first 'blog'" in 1992 to discuss the progress made on creating the World Wide Web and software used for it.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] From June 14, 1993, Mosaic Communications Corporation maintained their "What's New" list of new websites, updated daily and archived monthly.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The page was accessible by a special "What's New" button in the Mosaic web browser.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In November 1993 Ranjit Bhatnagar started writing about interesting sites, pages and discussion groups he found on the internet, as well as some personal information, on his website Moonmilk, arranging them chronologically in a special section called Ranjit's HTTP Playground.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Other early pioneers of blogging, such as Justin Hall, credit him with being an inspiration.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The earliest instance of a commercial blog was on the first business to consumer Web site created in 1995 by Ty, Inc., which featured a blog in a section called "Online Diary".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The entries were maintained by featured Beanie Babies that were voted for monthly by Web site visitors.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The modern blog evolved from the online diary where people would keep a running account of the events in their personal lives.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Most such writers called themselves diarists, journalists, or journalers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Justin Hall, who began personal blogging in 1994 while a student at Swarthmore College, is generally recognized as one of the earlier bloggers, as is Jerry Pournelle.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Dave Winer's Scripting News is also credited with being one of the older and longer running weblogs.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The Australian Netguide magazine maintained the Daily Net News on their web site from 1996.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Daily Net News ran links and daily reviews of new websites, mostly in Australia.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Another early blog was Wearable Wireless Webcam, an online shared diary of a person's personal life combining text, digital video, and digital pictures transmitted live from a wearable computer and EyeTap device to a web site in 1994.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This practice of semi-automated blogging with live video together with text was referred to as sousveillance, and such journals were also used as evidence in legal matters.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Some early bloggers, such as The Misanthropic Bitch, who began in 1997, referred to their online presence as a zine, before the term blog entered common usage.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Early blogs were simply manually updated components of common Websites.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In 1995, the "Online Diary" on the Ty, Inc.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Web site was produced and updated manually before any blogging programs were available.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Posts were made to appear in reverse chronological order by manually updating text-based HTML code using FTP software in real time several times a day.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] To users, this offered the appearance of a live diary that contained multiple new entries per day.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] At the beginning of each new day, new diary entries were manually coded into a new HTML file, and at the start of each month, diary entries were archived into their own folder, which contained a separate HTML page for every day of the month.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Then, menus that contained links to the most recent diary entry were updated manually throughout the site.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This text-based method of organizing thousands of files served as a springboard to define future blogging styles that were captured by blogging software developed years later.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The evolution of electronic and software tools to facilitate the production and maintenance of Web articles posted in reverse chronological order made the publishing process feasible for a much larger and less technically inclined population.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Ultimately, this resulted in the distinct class of online publishing that produces blogs we recognize today.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] For instance, the use of some sort of browser-based software is now a typical aspect of "blogging".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs can be hosted by dedicated blog hosting services, on regular web hosting services, or run using blog software.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] After a slow start, blogging rapidly gained in popularity.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] An early milestone in the rise in importance of blogs came in 2002, when many bloggers focused on comments by U.S.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Senator Strom Thurmond, praised Senator Thurmond by suggesting that the United States would have been better off had Thurmond been elected president.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Lott's critics saw these comments as tacit approval of racial segregation, a policy advocated by Thurmond's 1948 presidential campaign.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This view was reinforced by documents and recorded interviews dug up by bloggers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] (See Josh Marshall's *Talking Points Memo*.) Though Lott's comments were made at a public event attended by the media, no major media organizations reported on his controversial comments until after blogs broke the story.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogging helped to create a political crisis that forced Lott to step down as majority leader.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Similarly, blogs were among the driving forces behind the "Rathergate" scandal.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Television journalist Dan Rather presented documents on the CBS show *60 Minutes* that conflicted with accepted accounts of President Bush's military service record.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Bloggers declared the documents to be forgeries and presented evidence and arguments in support of that view.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Consequently, CBS apologized for what it said were inadequate reporting techniques (see: Little Green Footballs).
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The impact of these stories gave greater credibility to blogs as a medium of news dissemination.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In Russia, some political bloggers have started to challenge the dominance of official, overwhelmingly pro-government media.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Bloggers such as Rustem Adagamov and Alexei Navalny have many followers, and the latter's nickname for the ruling United Russia party as the "party of crooks and thieves" has been adopted by anti-regime protesters.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This led to *The Wall Street Journal* calling Navalny "the man Vladimir Putin fears most" in March 2012.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] By 2004, the role of blogs became increasingly mainstream, as political consultants, news services, and candidates began using them as tools for outreach and opinion forming.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogging was established by politicians and political candidates to express opinions on war and other issues and cemented blogs' role as a news source.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] (See Howard Dean and Wesley Clark.) Even politicians not actively campaigning, such as the UK's Labour Party's Member of Parliament (MP) Tom Watson, began to blog to bond with constituents.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In January 2005, *Fortune* magazine listed eight bloggers whom business people "could not ignore": Peter Rojas, Xeni Jardin, Ben Trott, Mena Trott, Jonathan Schwartz, Jason Goldman, Robert Scoble, and Jason Calacanis.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Israel was among the first national governments to set up an official blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Under David Saranga, the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs became active in adopting Web 2.0 initiatives, including an official video blog and a political blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The Foreign Ministry also held a microblogging press conference via Twitter about its war with Hamas, with Saranga answering questions from the public in common text-messaging abbreviations during a live worldwide press conference.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The questions and answers were later posted on IsraelPolitik, the country's official political blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The impact of blogging on the mainstream media has also been acknowledged by governments.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In 2009, the presence of the American journalism industry had declined to the point that several newspaper corporations were filing for bankruptcy, resulting in less direct competition between newspapers within the same circulation area.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Discussion emerged as to whether the newspaper industry would benefit from a stimulus package by the federal government.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Between 2009 and 2012, an Orwell Prize for blogging was awarded.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the late 2000s, blogs were often used on business websites and for grassroots political activism.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] There are many different types of blogs, differing not only in the type of content, but also in the way that content is delivered or written.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The personal blog is an ongoing online diary or commentary written by an individual, rather than a corporation or organization.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] While the vast majority of personal blogs attract very few readers, other than the blogger's immediate family and friends, a small number of personal blogs have become popular, to the point that they have attracted lucrative advertising sponsorship.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A few personal bloggers have gained significant recognition beyond their immediate circles.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A type of weblog in which posts are written and published by more than one author.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The majority of high-profile collaborative blogs are organised according to a single uniting theme, such as politics, technology or advocacy.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] has seen the emergence and growing popularity of more collaborative efforts, often set up by already established bloggers wishing to pool time and resources, both to reduce the pressure of maintaining a popular website and to attract a larger readership.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Microblogging is the practice of posting small pieces of digital content—which could be text, pictures, links, short videos, or other media—on the internet.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Microblogging offers a portable communication mode that feels organic and spontaneous to many users.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] It has captured the public imagination, in part because the short posts are easy to read on the go or when waiting.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Friends use it to keep in touch, business associates use it to coordinate meetings or share useful resources, and celebrities and politicians (or their publicists) microblog about concert dates, lectures, book releases, or tour schedules.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A wide and growing range of add-on tools enables sophisticated updates and interaction with other applications.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The resulting profusion of functionality is helping to define new possibilities for this type of communication.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] who makes posts in the style of the credited author.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Similar blogs for clubs and societies are called club blogs, group blogs, or by similar names; typical use is to inform members and other interested parties of club and member activities.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Individuals or organization may aggregate selected feeds on a specific topic, product or service and provide a combined view for its readers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This allows readers to concentrate on reading instead of searching for quality on-topic content and managing subscriptions.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs that are written on typewriters and then scanned are called typecast or typecast blogs.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A blog can also be defined by which type of device is used to compose it.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Such journals have been used as evidence in legal matters.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A reverse blog is composed by its users rather than a single blogger.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This system has the characteristics of a blog and the writing of several authors.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] These can be written by several contributing authors on a topic or opened up for anyone to write.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] (refbacks, trackbacks or pingbacks), and backlinks.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Discussions "in the blogosphere" were occasionally used by the media as a gauge of public opinion on various issues.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] pay close attention to "trends in the blogosphere".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] exist that connect people to blogs and bloggers to other bloggers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Interest-specific blogging platforms are also available.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] For instance, Blogster has a sizable community of political bloggers among its members.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] or promotional content, either to financially benefit the blogger, support website hosting costs, or to promote the blogger's favourite causes or products.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] in which a company will create a fictional blog as a marketing tool to promote a product.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] As the popularity of blogging continued to rise (as of 2006), the commercialisation of blogging is rapidly increasing.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Many corporations and companies collaborate with bloggers to increase advertising and engage online communities with their products.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the book *Fans, Bloggers, and Gamers*, Henry Jenkins stated that "Bloggers take knowledge into their own hands, enabling successful navigation within and between these emerging knowledge cultures.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs are a form of websites and can therefore be created via the same software as can be used for creating websites.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Many people use managed platforms such as Medium (website) or Substack.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] These platforms have built-in support for many features such as previewing posts, paywalls, and newsletters.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Other people self-host their website via open source software such as WordPress or static site generators such as Hugo (software) or Jekyll (software).
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Many bloggers, particularly those engaged in participatory journalism, are amateur journalists, and thus they differentiate themselves from the professional reporters and editors who work in mainstream media organizations.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Other bloggers are media professionals who are publishing online, rather than via a TV station or newspaper, either as an add-on to a traditional media presence (e.g., hosting a radio show or writing a column in a paper newspaper), or as their sole journalistic output.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Some institutions and organizations see blogging as a means of "getting around the filter" of media "gatekeepers" and pushing their messages directly to the public.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Many mainstream journalists, meanwhile, write their own blogs—well over 300, according to CyberJournalist.net's J-blog list.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The first known use of a blog on a news site was in August 1998, when Jonathan Dube of *The Charlotte Observer* published one chronicling Hurricane Bonnie.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Some bloggers have moved over to other media.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In counterpoint, Hugh Hewitt exemplifies a mass media personality who has moved in the other direction, adding to his reach in "old media" by being an influential blogger.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs have also had an influence on minority languages, bringing together scattered speakers and learners; this is particularly so with blogs in Gaelic languages.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Minority language publishing (which may lack economic feasibility) can find its audience through inexpensive blogging.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] There are examples of bloggers who have published books based on their blogs, e.g., Salam Pax, Ellen Simonetti, Jessica Cutler, and ScrappleFace.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blog-based books have been given the name blook.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] A prize for the best blog-based book was initiated in 2005, the Lulu Blooker Prize.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] However, success has been elusive offline, with many of these books not selling as well as their blogs.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The book based on Julie Powell's blog "The Julie/Julia Project" was made into the film *Julie & Julia*, apparently the first to do so.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Consumer-generated advertising is a relatively new and controversial development, and it has created a new model of marketing communication from businesses to consumers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Among the various forms of advertising on blog, the most controversial are the sponsored posts.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] These are blog entries or posts and may be in the form of feedback, reviews, opinion, videos, etc. and usually contain a link back to the desired site using a keyword or several keywords.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs have led to some disintermediation and a breakdown of the traditional advertising model, where companies can skip over the advertising agencies (previously the only interface with the customer) and contact the customers directly via social media websites.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] On the other hand, new companies specialised in blog advertising have been established to take advantage of this new development as well.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] However, there are many people who look negatively on this new development.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Some believe that any form of commercial activity on blogs will destroy the blogosphere's credibility.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogging can result in a range of legal liabilities and other unforeseen consequences.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Several cases have been brought before the national courts against bloggers concerning issues of defamation or liability.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] U.S. payouts related to blogging totalled $17.4 million by 2009; in some cases these have been covered by umbrella insurance.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The courts have returned with mixed verdicts.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Internet service providers (ISPs), in general, are immune from liability for information that originates with third parties (U.S.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Communications Decency Act and the EU Directive 2000/31/EC).
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Cahill*, the Delaware Supreme Court held that stringent standards had to be met to unmask the anonymous bloggers and also took the unusual step of dismissing the libel case itself (as unfounded under American libel law) rather than referring it back to the trial court for reconsideration.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In a bizarre twist, the Cahills were able to obtain the identity of John Doe, who turned out to be the person they suspected: the town's mayor, Councilman Cahill's political rival.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The Cahills amended their original complaint, and the mayor settled the case rather than going to trial.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In January 2007, two prominent Malaysian political bloggers, Jeff Ooi and Ahirudin Attan, were sued by a pro-government newspaper, The New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad, Kalimullah bin Masheerul Hassan, Hishamuddin bin Aun and Brenden John a/l John Pereira over alleged defamation.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The plaintiff was supported by the Malaysian government.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Following the suit, the Malaysian government proposed to "register" all bloggers in Malaysia to better control parties against their interests.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This is the first such legal case against bloggers in the country.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In the United States, blogger Aaron Wall was sued by Traffic Power for defamation and publication of trade secrets in 2005.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] According to *Wired* magazine, Traffic Power had been "banned from Google for allegedly rigging search engine results." Wall and other "white hat" search engine optimization consultants had exposed Traffic Power in what they claim was an effort to protect the public.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The case was dismissed for lack of personal jurisdiction, and Traffic Power failed to appeal within the allowed time.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In 2009, NDTV issued a legal notice to Indian blogger Kunte for a blog post criticizing their coverage of the Mumbai attacks.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The blogger unconditionally withdrew his post, which resulted in several Indian bloggers criticizing NDTV for trying to silence critics.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In general, attempts by employee bloggers to protect themselves by maintaining anonymity have proved ineffective.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In 2009, a controversial and landmark decision by The Hon.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Mr Justice Eady refused to grant an order to protect the anonymity of Richard Horton.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Horton was a police officer in the United Kingdom who blogged about his job under the name "NightJack".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Delta Air Lines fired flight attendant Ellen Simonetti because she posted photographs of herself in uniform on an aeroplane and because of comments posted on her blog "Queen of Sky: Diary of a Flight Attendant" which the employer deemed inappropriate.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] This case highlighted the issue of personal blogging and freedom of expression versus employer rights and responsibilities, and so it received wide media attention.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Simonetti took legal action against the airline for "wrongful termination, defamation of character and lost future wages".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The suit was postponed while Delta was in bankruptcy proceedings.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In early 2006, Erik Ringmar, a senior lecturer at the London School of Economics, was ordered by the convenor of his department to "take down and destroy" his blog in which he discussed the quality of education at the school.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Mark Jen was terminated in 2005 after 10 days of employment as an assistant product manager at Google for discussing corporate secrets on his personal blog, then called 99zeros and hosted on the Google-owned Blogger service.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] He blogged about unreleased products and company finances a week before the company's earnings announcement.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] He was fired two days after he complied with his employer's request to remove the sensitive material from his blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In India, blogger Gaurav Sabnis resigned from IBM after his posts questioned the claims made by a management school.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Jessica Cutler, aka "The Washingtonienne", blogged about her sex life while employed as a congressional assistant.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] After the blog was discovered and she was fired, she wrote a novel based on her experiences and blog: *The Washingtonienne: A Novel*.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] As of 2006, Cutler is being sued by one of her former lovers in a case that could establish the extent to which bloggers are obligated to protect the privacy of their real life associates.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Petite Anglaise, lost her job in Paris at a British accountancy firm because of blogging.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Although given in the blog in a fairly anonymous manner, some of the descriptions of the firm and some of its people were less than flattering.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Sanderson later won a compensation claim case against the British firm, however.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] On the other hand, Penelope Trunk wrote an upbeat article in *The Boston Globe* in 2006, entitled "Blogs 'essential' to a good career".
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] She was one of the first journalists to point out that a large portion of bloggers are professionals and that a well-written blog can help attract employers.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Business owners who blog about their business can also run into legal consequences.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Mark Cuban, owner of the Dallas Mavericks, was fined during the 2006 NBA playoffs for criticizing NBA officials on the court and in his blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogging can sometimes have unforeseen consequences in politically sensitive areas.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In some countries, Internet police or secret police may monitor blogs and arrest blog authors or commentators.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Blogs can be much harder to control than broadcast or print media because a person can create a blog whose authorship is hard to trace by using anonymity technology such as Tor.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] As a result, totalitarian and authoritarian regimes often seek to suppress blogs and punish those who maintain them.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In Singapore, two ethnic Chinese individuals were imprisoned under the country's anti-sedition law for posting anti-Muslim remarks in their blogs.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Egyptian blogger Kareem Amer was charged with insulting the Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak and an Islamic institution through his blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] It is the first time in the history of Egypt that a blogger was prosecuted.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] After a brief trial session that took place in Alexandria, the blogger was found guilty and sentenced to prison terms of three years for insulting Islam and inciting sedition and one year for insulting Mubarak.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Egyptian blogger Abdel Monem Mahmoud was arrested in April 2007 for anti-government writings in his blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Monem is a member of the then banned Muslim Brotherhood.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] After the 2011 Egyptian revolution, the Egyptian blogger Maikel Nabil Sanad was charged with insulting the military for an article he wrote on his personal blog and sentenced to three years.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] After expressing opinions in his personal blog about the state of the Sudanese armed forces, Jan Pronk, United Nations Special Representative for Sudan, was given three days notice to leave Sudan.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] The Sudanese army had demanded his deportation.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In Myanmar, Nay Phone Latt, a blogger, was sentenced to 20 years in jail for posting a cartoon critical of head of state Than Shwe.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] One consequence of blogging is the possibility of online or in-person attacks or threats against the blogger, sometimes without apparent reason.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] In some cases, bloggers have faced cyberbullying.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Kathy Sierra, author of the blog "Creating Passionate Users", was the target of threats and misogynistic insults to the point that she cancelled her keynote speech at a technology conference in San Diego, fearing for her safety.
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] While a blogger's anonymity is often tenuous, Internet trolls who would attack a blogger with threats or insults can be emboldened by the anonymity of the online environment, where some users are known only by a pseudonymous "username" (e.g., "Hacker1984").
[src:wordpress-cms/blog-software] Sierra and supporters initiated an online discussion aimed at countering abusive online behaviour and developed a Blogger's Code of Conduct, which set out a rules for behaviour in the online space.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] A **content management system** (**CMS**) is a computer software used to manage the creation and modification of digital content (content management).
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] It is typically used for enterprise content management (ECM) and web content management (WCM).
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] ECM typically supports multiple users in a collaborative environment, by integrating document management, digital asset management, and record retention.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Alternatively, WCM is the collaborative authoring for websites and may include text and embed graphics, photos, video, audio, maps, and program code that display content and interact with the user.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] There are two types of CMS installation: on-premises and cloud-based.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] On-premises installation means that the CMS software can be installed on the server.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Notable CMSs which can be installed on-premises are Drupal, Grav, Joomla, ModX, Wordpress.org and others.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] The cloud-based CMS is hosted in the vendor's cloud environment.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Publishing architectures vary significantly between systems.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Traditional coupled CMSs tie the content repository to a single presentation layer, suiting organisations publishing to one channel.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Headless CMSs separate the repository from presentation entirely, delivering content via APIs to websites, mobile applications, digital signage, or voice interfaces from a single source, an approach that has grown rapidly alongside the proliferation of digital touchpoints.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Authoring environments typically enforce structured workflows in which content passes through defined review and approval stages before publication, with role-based permissions controlling what each user can create, edit, or publish.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] The core CMS features are: indexing, search and retrieval, format management, revision control, and management.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Digital asset management systems are another type of CMS.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] They manage content with clearly defined author or ownership, such as documents, movies, pictures, phone numbers, and scientific data.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Companies also use CMSs to store, control, revise, and publish documentation.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] There are also component content management systems (CCMS), which are CMSs that manage content at a modular level rather than as pages or articles.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] CCMSs are often used in technical communication, where many publications reuse the same content.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Headless CMS, which separates content from its delivery layer, offers greater flexibility in content distribution across various platforms.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] According to W3Techs, the most widely used content management system is WordPress, used by 61.7% of websites as of March 2026.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Other commonly used content management systems include Shopify, Wix, and Squarespace .
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] If the cross-reference mechanism is well designed, the reader will be able to follow each cross-reference to the referenced content whether the content is presented in print or electronically.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] An author working in a content management system is responsible for identifying subjects of interest that cross documents, and creating appropriate systems of cross-references to support readers who seek to understand those subjects.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] For an individual cross-reference, an author should ensure that location and content of the target of the cross-reference are clearly identified, and the reader can easily determine how to follow the cross-reference in each medium in which publication is supported.
[src:wordpress-cms/content-management-system] Content strategy practitioners (known as content strategists) specialize in planning content to meet business needs, taking into account the processes for creating and maintaining the content, and the systems that support the content.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP code is usually processed on a web server by a PHP interpreter implemented as a module, a daemon or a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) executable.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] On a web server, the result of the interpreted and executed PHP code—which may be any type of data, such as generated HTML or binary image data—can form the whole or part of an HTTP response.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Various web template systems, web content management systems, and web frameworks exist that can be employed to orchestrate or facilitate the generation of that response.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP can be used for programming tasks outside the web context, though non-web uses are rare.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP code can also be directly executed from the command line.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The standard PHP interpreter, powered by the Zend Engine, is free software released under the PHP License.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP has been widely ported and can be deployed on most web servers on a variety of operating systems and platforms.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The PHP language at first evolved without a written formal specification or standard, with the original implementation acting as the *de facto* standard that other implementations aimed to follow.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP development began in 1993 when Rasmus Lerdorf wrote several Common Gateway Interface (CGI) programs in C, which he used to maintain his personal homepage.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] He extended them to work with HTML forms and to communicate with databases, and called this implementation "Personal Home Page/Forms Interpreter" or PHP/FI.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP/FI could be used to build simple, dynamic web applications.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] To accelerate bug reporting and improve the code, Lerdorf initially announced the release of PHP/FI as "Personal Home Page Tools (PHP Tools) version 1.0" on the Usenet discussion group *comp.infosystems.www.authoring.cgi* on 8 June 1995.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This release included basic functionality such as Perl-like variables, form handling, and the ability to embed HTML.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] By this point, the syntax had changed to resemble that of Perl, but was simpler, more limited, and less consistent.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The fact that PHP was not originally designed, but instead was developed organically has led to inconsistent naming of functions and inconsistent ordering of their parameters.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In some cases, the function names were chosen to match the lower-level libraries which PHP was "wrapping", while in some very early versions of PHP the length of the function names was used internally as a hash function, so names were chosen to improve the distribution of hash values.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Zeev Suraski and Andi Gutmans rewrote the parser in 1997 and formed the base of PHP 3, changing the language's name to the recursive acronym *PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor*.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Afterwards, public testing of PHP 3 began, and the official launch came in June 1998.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Suraski and Gutmans then started a new rewrite of PHP's core, producing the Zend Engine in 1999.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] They also founded Zend Technologies in Ramat Gan, Israel.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] On 22 May 2000, PHP 4.0, powered by the Zend Engine 1.0, was released.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] By August 2008, this branch had reached version 4.4.9.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 4 is now no longer under development nor are any security updates planned to be released.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] On 1 July 2004, PHP 5.0 was released, powered by the new Zend Engine 2.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 5.0 included significant changes to the language, most notably an overhauled approach to object-oriented programming, as well as iterators and exceptions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 5.1 and PHP 5.2 were released the following years, adding smaller improvements and new features, such as the PHP Data Objects (PDO) extension (which defines a lightweight and consistent interface for accessing databases) In 2008, PHP 5.x became the only stable version under development.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Many high-profile open-source projects ceased to support PHP 4 in new code from February 5, 2008, because of the GoPHP5 initiative, provided by a consortium of PHP developers promoting the transition from PHP 4 to PHP 5.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP's native string functions worked only on raw bytes, making use with multibyte character encodings difficult.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In 2005, a project headed by Andrei Zmievski was initiated to bring native Unicode support throughout PHP, by embedding the International Components for Unicode (ICU) library, and representing text strings as UTF-16 internally.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Since this would cause major changes both to the internals of the language and to user code, it was planned to release this as version 6.0 of the language, along with other major features then in development.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] However, a shortage of developers who understood the necessary changes, and performance problems arising from conversion to and from UTF-16, which is rarely used in a web context, led to delays in the project.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] As a result, a PHP 5.3 release was created in 2009, and in March 2010, the project in its current form was officially abandoned, and a PHP 5.4 release was prepared to contain most remaining non-Unicode features from PHP 6.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Initial hopes were that a new plan would be formed for Unicode integration, but by 2014 none had been adopted.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Because it contained features originally intended to be part of 6.0, PHP 5.3 was a significant release, adding support for namespaces, closures, late static binding, and many fixes and improvements to standard functions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] With the Unicode branch officially abandoned, a new release process was adopted in 2011, planning a yearly release cycle, and a clear distinction between "feature releases" (x.y.z to x.y+1.z) and "major releases" (x.y.z to x+1.0.0).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Remaining features which had been planned for the 6.0 release were included in PHP 5.4, released in March 2012, such as trait support and a new "short array syntax".
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This was followed by more incremental changes in PHP 5.5 (June 2013) and 5.6 (August 2014).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] For PHP versions 5.3 and 5.4, the only available Microsoft Windows binary distributions were 32-bit IA-32 builds, requiring Windows 32-bit compatibility mode while using Internet Information Services (IIS) on a 64-bit Windows platform.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP version 5.5 made the 64-bit x86-64 builds available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Official security support for PHP 5.6 ended on 31 December 2018.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] During 2014 and 2015, a new major PHP version was developed, PHP 7.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The numbering of this version involved some debate among internal developers.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] While the PHP 6 Unicode experiments had never been released, several articles and book titles referenced the PHP 6 names, which might have caused confusion if a new release were to reuse the name.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] After a vote, the name PHP 7 was chosen.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The foundation of PHP 7.0 was a PHP branch that was originally dubbed *PHP next generation* (*phpng*).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] It was written by Dmitry Stogov, Xinchen Hui and Nikita Popov, and aimed to optimize PHP performance by refactoring the Zend Engine while retaining near-complete language compatibility.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] By 14 July 2014, WordPress-based benchmarks, which served as the main benchmark suite for the phpng project, showed an almost 100% increase in performance.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Changes from phpng make it easier to improve performance in future versions, as more compact data structures and other changes are seen as better suited for a successful migration to a just-in-time (JIT) compiler.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Because of the significant changes, the reworked Zend Engine was called *Zend Engine 3*, succeeding Zend Engine 2 used in PHP 5.x.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also included changes which were not backward compatible, as allowed for "major versions" under the versioning scheme agreed in 2011.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Changes to the core language included a more consistent handling of variable dereferencing, a more predictable behavior of the `foreach` statement, and platform consistency of bitwise shifts and floating-point to integer conversion.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Several unmaintained or deprecated server application programming interfaces (SAPIs) and extensions were removed from the PHP core, most notably the legacy `mysql` extension.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Other legacy features were also removed, such as ASP-style delimiters `<%` and `%>` and `<script language="php"> ... </script>`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 7.0 marked the beginning of an expansion in PHP's type system.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 8.0 was released on 26 November 2020, as a major version with breaking changes from previous versions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] One of the most high-profile changes was the addition of a JIT compiler, which can provide substantial performance improvements for some use cases.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Substantial improvements were expected more for mathematical-type operations than for common web-development use cases.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Additionally, the performance advantage of the JIT compiler provides the potential to move some code from C to PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] A significant addition to the language in 8.0 is attributes, which allow metadata to be added to program elements such as classes, methods, and parameters.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Later versions added built-in attributes which change the behaviour of the language, such as the `#[\SensitiveParameter]` attribute in PHP 8.2, `#[\Override]` in PHP 8.3, `#[\Deprecated]` in PHP 8.4, and the `#[\NoDiscard]` and `#[\DelayedTargetValidation]` attributes in PHP 8.5.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] A significant extension to the language's type system is the addition of composite types: union types in PHP 8.0 (e.g.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `int|string` meaning "either integer or string"), intersection types in PHP 8.1 (e.g.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `Traversable&Countable` meaning the value must implement both the `Traversable` and `Countable` interfaces), and disjunctive normal form (DNF) types in PHP 8.2 (unions of intersections, such as `array|(Traversable&Countable)`).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Additional special type keywords have been added, such as `mixed` and `static` in PHP 8.0, `never` (a bottom type indicating that a function never returns) in PHP 8.1, and `null`, `false`, and `true` as stand-alone types in PHP 8.2.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The addition of a rich type system is part of a general trend towards a stricter language, and PHP 8.0 included breaking changes to the handling of string to number comparisons, numeric strings, and incompatible method signatures.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Later versions have introduced deprecation notices for behaviour which is planned as a breaking change in a future major version, such as passing `null` to non-nullable internal function parameters and referring to properties which have not been declared on the class.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Beginning on 28 June 2011, the PHP Development Team implemented a timeline for the release of new versions of PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Under this system, at least one release should occur every month.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Once per year, a minor release should occur which may include new features.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Every minor release should at least be supported for two years with security and bug fixes, followed by at least one year of only security fixes, for a total of a three-year release process for every minor release.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] No new features, unless small and self-contained, are to be introduced into a minor release during the three-year release process.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] A 2024 RFC extended the length of the security fix only period to two years, fixed all end of life dates to 31 December, and removed the exception that allowed for "small and self-contained" features to be introduced in patch versions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] W3Techs reports that as of November 2025 (about three years since PHP 7 was discontinued and 23 months after the PHP 8.3 release), unsupported versions such as PHP 7 are still used by well over half of PHP websites, which are outdated and known to be insecure.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Those included the 9.7% of PHP websites using the even more outdated (discontinued for 7 years) and insecure PHP 5, released over two decades ago.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The mascot of the PHP project is the *elePHPant*, a blue elephant with the PHP logo on its side, designed by Vincent Pontier in 1998.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The elePHPant is sometimes differently coloured when in plush toy form.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Many variations of this physical mascot have been made over the years.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Only the elePHPants based on the original design by Vincent Pontier are considered official by the community.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] These are collectable and some of them are extremely rare.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The PHP interpreter only executes PHP code within its delimiters.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Anything outside its delimiters is not processed by PHP, although the non-PHP text can still be subject to control structures described in PHP code.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `<?php` is used to open and `?>` to close PHP sections.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] A shorthand `<?=` exists, which is a shorthand for `<?php echo`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The shortened form `<?` also exists, which makes script files less portable since support can be disabled in the local PHP configuration.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The shortened form is discouraged by the PHP Group for this reason.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Conversely, there is no recommendation against the echo short tag `<?=`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Prior to PHP 5.4.0, the short syntax for `echo` only works with the `short_open_tag` configuration setting enabled, while for PHP 5.4.0 and later it is always available.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The purpose of delimiters is to separate PHP code from non-PHP content, such as JavaScript code or HTML markup.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The first form of delimiters, `<?php` and `?>`, in XHTML and other XML documents, creates correctly formed XML processing instructions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This means that the resulting mixture of PHP code and other markup in the server-side file is itself well-formed XML.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Variables are prefixed with a dollar symbol, and a type does not need to be specified in advance.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced type declarations that allow functions to force their parameters to be objects of a specific class, arrays, interfaces or callback functions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] However, before PHP 7, type declarations could not be used with scalar types such as integers or strings.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Below is an example of how PHP variables are declared and initialized.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Unlike function and class names, variable names are case-sensitive.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Both double-quoted ("") and heredoc strings provide the ability to interpolate a variable's value into the string.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP treats newlines as whitespace in the manner of a free-form language, and statements are terminated by a semicolon.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP has three types of comments: `/* */` marks block and inline comments; `//` or `#` are used for one-line comments.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The `echo` statement is one of several keywords PHP provides to output text.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In terms of keywords and language syntax, PHP is similar to C-style syntax.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `if` conditions, `for` and `while` loops and function returns are similar in syntax to languages such as C, C++, C#, Java and Perl.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] It stores integers in a platform-dependent range, either as a 32, 64 or 128-bit signed integer equivalent to the C-language long type.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Unsigned integers are converted to signed values in certain situations, which is different behaviour to many other programming languages.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Integer variables can be assigned using decimal (positive and negative), octal, hexadecimal, and binary notations.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Floating-point numbers are also stored in a platform-specific range.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] They can be specified using floating-point notation, or two forms of scientific notation.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP has a native Boolean type that is similar to the native Boolean types in Java and C++.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Using the Boolean type conversion rules, non-zero values are interpreted as true and zero as false, as in Perl and C++.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The null data type represents a variable that has no value; `NULL` is the only allowed value for this data type.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Variables of the "resource" type represent references to resources from external sources.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] These are typically created by functions from a particular extension, and can only be processed by functions from the same extension; examples include file, image, and database resources.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Arrays can contain elements of any type that PHP can handle, including resources, objects, and even other arrays.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Order is preserved in lists of values and in hashes with both keys and values, and the two can be intermingled.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP also supports strings, which can be used with single quotes, double quotes, nowdoc or heredoc syntax.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The **Standard PHP Library** (SPL) attempts to solve standard problems and implements efficient data access interfaces and classes.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP defines a large array of functions in the core language and many are also available in various extensions; these functions are well documented online PHP documentation.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] However, the built-in library has a wide variety of naming conventions and associated inconsistencies, as described under history above.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In lieu of function pointers, functions in PHP can be referenced by a string containing their name.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In this manner, normal PHP functions can be used, for example, as callbacks or within function tables.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] User-defined functions may be created at any time without being prototyped.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Functions may be defined inside code blocks, permitting a run-time decision as to whether or not a function should be defined.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There is a `function_exists` function that determines whether a function with a given name has already been defined.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Function calls must use parentheses, with the exception of zero-argument class constructor functions called with the PHP operator `new`, in which case parentheses are optional.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In the example above, `getAdder()` function creates a closure using passed argument `$x`, which takes an additional argument `$y`, and returns the created closure to the caller.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Such a function is a first-class object, meaning that it can be stored in a variable, passed as a parameter to other functions, etc.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Unusually for a dynamically typed language, PHP supports type declarations on function parameters, which are enforced at runtime.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This has been supported for classes and interfaces since PHP 5.0, for arrays since PHP 5.1, for "callables" since PHP 5.4, and scalar (integer, float, string and boolean) types since PHP 7.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also has type declarations for function return types, expressed by placing the type name after the list of parameters, preceded by a colon.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] By default, scalar type declarations follow weak typing principles.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] So, for example, if a parameter's type is `int`, PHP would allow not only integers, but also convertible numeric strings, floats or Booleans to be passed to that function, and would convert them.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] However, PHP 7 has a "strict typing" mode which, when used, disallows such conversions for function calls and returns within a file.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Basic object-oriented programming functionality was added in PHP 3 and improved in PHP 4.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This allowed for PHP to gain further abstraction, making creative tasks easier for programmers using the language.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Object handling was completely rewritten for PHP 5, expanding the feature set and enhancing performance.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In previous versions of PHP, objects were handled like value types.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The drawback of this method was that code had to make heavy use of PHP's "reference" variables if it wanted to modify an object it was passed rather than creating a copy of it.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] In the new approach, objects are referenced by handle, and not by value.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced private and protected member variables and methods, along with abstract classes, final classes, abstract methods, and final methods.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] It also introduced a standard way of declaring constructors and destructors, similar to that of other object-oriented languages such as C++, and a standard exception handling model.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Furthermore, PHP 5 added interfaces and allowed for multiple interfaces to be implemented.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There are special interfaces that allow objects to interact with the runtime system.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Objects implementing ArrayAccess can be used with array syntax and objects implementing Iterator or IteratorAggregate can be used with the `foreach` language construct.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There is no virtual table feature in the engine, so static variables are bound with a name instead of a reference at compile time.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] If the developer creates a copy of an object using the reserved word `clone`, the Zend engine will check whether a `__clone()` method has been defined.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] If not, it will call a default `__clone()` which will copy the object's properties.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] If a `__clone()` method is defined, then it will be responsible for setting the necessary properties in the created object.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] For convenience, the engine will supply a function that imports the properties of the source object, so the programmer can start with a by-value replica of the source object and only override properties that need to be changed.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The visibility of PHP properties and methods is defined using the keywords `public`, `private`, and `protected`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The default is public, if only var is used; `var` is a synonym for `public`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Items declared `public` can be accessed everywhere.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `protected` limits access to inherited classes (and to the class that defines the item).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] `private` limits visibility only to the class that defines the item.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Objects of the same type have access to each other's private and protected members even though they are not the same instance.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The only complete PHP implementation is the original, known simply as PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] It is the most widely used and is powered by the Zend Engine.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] To disambiguate it from other implementations, it is sometimes unofficially called "Zend PHP".
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The Zend Engine compiles PHP source code on-the-fly into an internal format that it can execute, thus it works as an interpreter.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] It is also the "reference implementation" of PHP, as PHP has no formal specification, and so the semantics of Zend PHP define the semantics of PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Due to the complex and nuanced semantics of PHP, defined by how Zend works, it is difficult for competing implementations to offer complete compatibility.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP's single-request-per-script-execution model, and the fact that the Zend Engine is an interpreter, leads to inefficiency; as a result, various products have been developed to help improve PHP performance.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] An opcode cache, Zend Opcache, is built into PHP since version 5.5.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Another example of a widely used opcode cache is the Alternative PHP Cache (APC), which is available as a PECL extension.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] While Zend PHP is still the most popular implementation, several other implementations have been developed.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Some of these are compilers or support JIT compilation, and hence offer performance benefits over Zend PHP at the expense of lacking full PHP compatibility.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP is free software released under the PHP License, which is equivalent to the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] This restriction on the use of "PHP" made the PHP License incompatible with the GNU General Public License (GPL), while the Zend License was incompatible due to an advertising clause similar to that of the original BSD license.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP includes various free and open-source libraries in its source distribution or uses them in resulting PHP binary builds.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP is fundamentally an Internet-aware system with built-in modules for accessing File Transfer Protocol (FTP) servers and many database servers, including PostgreSQL, MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server and SQLite (which is an embedded database), LDAP servers, and others.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Numerous functions are familiar to C programmers, such as those in the stdio family, are available in standard PHP builds.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP allows developers to write extensions in C to add functionality to the PHP language.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP extensions can be compiled statically into PHP or loaded dynamically at runtime.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Numerous extensions have been written to add support for the Windows API, process management on Unix-like operating systems, multibyte strings (Unicode), cURL, and several popular compression formats.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Other PHP features made available through extensions include integration with Internet Relay Chat (IRC), dynamic generation of images and Adobe Flash content, *PHP Data Objects* (PDO) as an abstraction layer used for accessing databases, and even speech synthesis.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Some of the language's core functions, such as those dealing with strings and arrays, are also implemented as extensions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The PHP Extension Community Library (PECL) project is a repository for extensions to the PHP language.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Most of the community focuses on web development, and PHP running server side (though also serving JavaScript for the client side), and some exceptional uses are for e.g. standalone graphical applications (with PHP-GTK unmaintained now for over a decade), and even drone control.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Some other projects, such as *Zephir*, provide the ability for PHP extensions to be created in a high-level language and compiled into native PHP extensions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Such an approach, instead of writing PHP extensions directly in C, simplifies the development of extensions and reduces the time required for programming and testing.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] By December 2018 the PHP Group consisted of ten people: Thies C.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Arntzen, Stig Bakken, Shane Caraveo, Andi Gutmans, Rasmus Lerdorf, Sam Ruby, Sascha Schumann, Zeev Suraski, Jim Winstead, and Andrei Zmievski.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Zend Technologies provides a PHP Certification based on PHP 8 exam (and previously based on PHP 7 and 5.5) for programmers to become certified PHP developers.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] On 26 November 2021, the JetBrains blog announced the creation of The PHP Foundation, which will sponsor the design and development of PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The foundation hires "Core Developers" to work on the PHP language's core repository.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Roman Pronskiy, a member of the foundation's board, said that they aim to pay "market salaries" to developers.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The response to the foundation has been largely positive.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund provided more than 200,000 Euros to support the PHP Foundation.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There are two primary ways for adding support for PHP to a web server – as a native web server module, or as a CGI executable.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP has a direct module interface called server application programming interface (SAPI), which is supported by many web servers including Apache HTTP Server, Microsoft IIS, Caddy (through FrankenPHP) and iPlanet Web Server.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Some other web servers, such as OmniHTTPd, support the Internet Server Application Programming Interface (ISAPI), which is Microsoft's web server module interface.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] If PHP has no module support for a web server, it can always be used as a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) or FastCGI processor; in that case, the web server is configured to use PHP's CGI executable to process all requests to PHP files.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP-FPM (FastCGI Process Manager) is an alternative FastCGI implementation for PHP, bundled with the official PHP distribution since version 5.3.3.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] When compared to the older FastCGI implementation, it contains some additional features, mostly useful for heavily loaded web servers.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] When using PHP for command-line scripting, a PHP command-line interface (CLI) executable is needed.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP supports a CLI server application programming interface (SAPI) since PHP 4.3.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The main focus of this SAPI is developing shell applications using PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There are quite a few differences between the CLI SAPI and other SAPIs, although they do share many of the same behaviours.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] There are different kinds of SAPIs for various web server extensions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] For example, in addition to those listed above, other SAPIs for the PHP language include the Common Gateway Interface and command-line interface.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP can also be used for writing desktop graphical user interface (GUI) applications, by using the *"PHP Desktop".
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] *GitHub*.* or discontinued PHP-GTK extension.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] PHP-GTK is not included in the official PHP distribution, and as an extension, it can be used only with PHP versions 5.1.0 and newer.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The most common way of installing PHP-GTK is by compiling it from the source code.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] When PHP is installed and used in cloud environments, software development kits (SDKs) are provided for using cloud-specific features.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Numerous configuration options are supported, affecting both core PHP features and extensions.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] Configuration file `php.ini` is searched for in different locations, depending on the way PHP is used.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p01] The configuration file is split into various sections, while some of the configuration options can be also set within the web server configuration.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP is a general-purpose scripting language that is especially suited to server-side web development, in which case PHP generally runs on a web server.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Any PHP code in a requested file is executed by the PHP runtime, usually to create dynamic web page content or dynamic images used on websites or elsewhere.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] It can also be used for command-line scripting and client-side graphical user interface (GUI) applications.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP can be deployed on most web servers, many operating systems and platforms, and can be used with many relational database management systems (RDBMS).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Most web hosting providers support PHP for use by their clients.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] It is available free of charge, and the PHP Group provides the complete source code for users to build, customize and extend for their own use.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP has also attracted the development of many software frameworks that provide building blocks and a design structure to promote rapid application development (RAD).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Some of these include PRADO, CakePHP, Symfony, CodeIgniter, Laravel, Yii Framework, Phalcon and Laminas, offering features similar to other web frameworks.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] The LAMP architecture has become popular in the web industry as a way of deploying web applications.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP is commonly used as the *P* in this bundle alongside Linux, Apache and MySQL, although the *P* may also refer to Python, Perl, or some mix of the three.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Similar packages, WAMP and MAMP, are also available for Windows and macOS, with the first letter standing for the respective operating system.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Although both PHP and Apache are provided as part of the macOS base install, users of these packages seek a simpler installation mechanism that can be more easily kept up to date.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] For specific and more advanced usage scenarios, PHP offers a well-defined and documented way for writing custom extensions in C or C++.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Besides extending the language itself in form of additional libraries, extensions are providing a way for improving execution speed where it is critical and there is room for improvements by using a true compiled language.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP also offers well-defined ways for embedding itself into other software projects.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] That way PHP can be easily used as an internal scripting language for another project, also providing tight interfacing with the project's specific internal data structures.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP received mixed reviews due to lacking support for multithreading at the core language level, though using threads is made possible by the "pthreads" PECL extension.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] A command line interface, php-cli, and two ActiveX Windows Script Host scripting engines for PHP have been produced.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP is used for Web content management systems including MediaWiki, WordPress, Joomla, Drupal, Moodle, eZ Publish, eZ Platform, and SilverStripe.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] As of January 2013, PHP was used in more than 240 million websites (39% of those sampled) and was installed on 2.1 million web servers.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] In 2019, 11% of all vulnerabilities listed by the National Vulnerability Database were linked to PHP; historically, about 30% of all vulnerabilities listed since 1996 in this database are linked to PHP.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Technical security flaws of the language itself or of its core libraries are not frequent (22 in 2009, about 1% of the total although PHP applies to about 20% of programs listed).
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Recognizing that programmers make mistakes, some languages include taint checking to automatically detect the lack of input validation which induces many issues.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Such a feature has been proposed for PHP in the past, but either been rejected or the proposal abandoned.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Third-party projects such as Suhosin and Snuffleupagus aim to remove or change dangerous parts of the language.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Historically, old versions of PHP had some configuration parameters and default values for such runtime settings that made some PHP applications prone to security issues.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Support for "magic quotes" and "register globals" settings has been deprecated since PHP 5.3.0, and removed from PHP 5.4.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] The best practice is to either locate the image directory outside the document root available to the web server and serve it via an intermediary script or disable PHP execution for the directory which stores the uploaded files.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Also, enabling the dynamic loading of PHP extensions (via `enable_dl` configuration directive) in a shared web hosting environment can lead to security issues.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Implied type conversions that result in different values being treated as equal, sometimes against the programmer's intent, can lead to security issues.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] For example, the result of the comparison `'0e1234' == '0'` is `true`, because strings that are parsable as numbers are converted to numbers; in this case, the first compared value is treated as scientific notation having the value (0×101234), which is zero.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] Errors like this resulted in authentication vulnerabilities in Simple Machines Forum, Typo3 and phpBB when MD5 password hashes were compared.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] The recommended way is to use `hash_equals()` (for timing attack safety), `strcmp` or the identity operator (`===`), as `'0e1234' === '0'` results in `false`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] In a 2013 analysis of over 170,000 website defacements, published by Zone-H, the most frequently (53%) used technique was the exploitation of file inclusion vulnerability, mostly related to insecure usage of the PHP language constructs `include`, `require`, and `allow_url_fopen`.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] PHP includes `rand()` and `mt_rand()` functions which use a pseudorandom number generator, and are not cryptographically secure.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] As of version 8.1, the `random_int()` function is included, which uses a cryptographically secure source of randomness provided by the system.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] There are two attacks that can be performed over PHP entropy sources: "seed attack" and "state recovery attack".
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] As of 2012, a $250 GPU can perform up to 230 MD5 calculations per second, while a $750 GPU can perform four times as many calculations at the same time.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] In combination with a "birthday attack" this can lead to serious security vulnerabilities.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] The PHP development team provides official bug fixes for two years following release of each minor version followed by another two years where only security fixes are released.
[src:wordpress-cms/php-p02] After this, the release is considered end of life and no longer officially supported.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] In computing, a **plug-in** (also spelled **plugin**), **add-in** (also **addin**, **add-on**, or **addon**) or **extension** is a software component that extends the functionality of an existing software system without requiring the system to be re-built.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] A plug-in feature is one way that a system can be customizable.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] The host application provides services which the plug-in can use, including a way for plug-ins to register themselves with the host application and a protocol for the exchange of data with plug-ins.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Plug-ins depend on the services provided by the host application and do not usually work by themselves.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Conversely, the host application operates independently of the plug-ins, making it possible for end-users to add and update plug-ins dynamically without needing to make changes to the host application.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Programmers typically implement plug-ins as shared libraries, which get dynamically loaded at run time.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] HyperCard supported a similar facility, but more commonly included the plug-in code in the HyperCard documents (called *stacks*) themselves.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Thus the HyperCard stack became a self-contained application in its own right, distributable as a single entity that end-users could run without the need for additional installation-steps.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Programs may also implement plug-ins by loading a directory of simple script files written in a scripting language like Python or Lua.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] In the context of a web browser, a helper application is a separate program—like IrfanView or Adobe Reader—that extends the functionality of a browser.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] A helper application extends the functionality an application but unlike the typical plug-in that is loaded into the host application's address space, a helper application is a separate application.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] With a separate address space, the extension cannot crash the host application as is possible if they share an address space.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] In the mid-1970s, the EDT text editor ran on the Unisys VS/9 operating system for the UNIVAC Series 90 mainframe computer.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] It allowed a program to be run from the editor, which can access the in-memory edit buffer.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] The plug-in executable could call the editor to inspect and change the text.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] The University of Waterloo Fortran compiler used this to allow interactive compilation of Fortran programs.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] Early personal computer software with plug-in capability included HyperCard and QuarkXPress on the Apple Macintosh, both released in 1987.
[src:wordpress-cms/plugin-computing] In 1988, Silicon Beach Software included plug-in capability in Digital Darkroom and SuperPaint.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] In computing, a **theme** is a preset package containing graphical appearance and functionality details.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] A theme usually comprises a set of shapes and colors for the graphical control elements, the window decoration and the window.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Themes are used to customize the look and feel of a piece of computer software or of an operating system.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] As such, a skin can completely change the look and feel and navigation interface of a piece of application software or operating system.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Software that is capable of having a skin applied is referred to as being **skinnable**, and the process of writing or applying such a skin is known as **skinning**.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Applying a skin changes a piece of software's look and feel—some skins merely make the program more aesthetically pleasing, but others can rearrange elements of the interface, potentially making the program easier to use.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Themes are often used to change the look and feel of a wide range of things at once, which makes them much less granular than allowing the user to set each option individually.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] For example, users might want the window-borders from a particular theme, but installing it would also alter the desktop background.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] One method for dealing with this is to allow the user to select which parts of the theme they want to load; for example in Windows 98, users could load the background and screensaver from a theme, but leave the icons and sounds untouched.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] add-on package also includes support for themes as well.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] uses themes to customize its taskbar, window borders, and time format.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] can store colors for icons, menus, and window-borders in a theme, but this is independent of the wallpaper settings.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] or list elements), and another theme to customize the appearance of windows (such as, window borders and title bars).
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] The CM theme engine is in turn used on many other forked Android ROMs, such as Paranoid Android.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Firefox and Google Chrome either support or supported a form of theme.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Firefox (and its sibling Thunderbird) supports themes either through *lightweight themes* (formerly Personas).
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Google Chrome version 3.0 or later allows themes to alter the appearance of the browser.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Internet Explorer 5 and its immediate successor allowed the background picture of their toolbars to be customized.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] The most popular skins are for instant messaging clients, media center, and media player software, such as Trillian and Winamp, due to the association with fun that such programs try to encourage.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Some platforms support changing the standard interface, including most using the X Window System.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] For those that do not, programs can add the functionality, like WindowBlinds for Microsoft Windows and ShapeShifter for macOS.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Many websites are skinnable, particularly those that provide social capabilities.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] Some sites provide skins that make primarily cosmetic changes, while some—such as H2G2—offer skins that make major changes to page layout.
[src:wordpress-cms/theme-computing] As with standalone software interfaces, this is facilitated by the underlying technology of the website—XML and XSLT, for instance, facilitate major changes of layout, while CSS can easily produce different visual styles.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress is written in the PHP programming language and paired with a MySQL or MariaDB database.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Features include a plugin architecture and a template system, known as “themes”.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Since 2018, WordPress has included a block-based editor (“Gutenberg”).
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] To function, WordPress has to be installed on a web server, either as part of an Internet hosting service or on a personal computer.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress was first released on May 27, 2003, by its founders, American developer Matt Mullenweg and English developer Mike Little.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The WordPress Foundation owns WordPress, WordPress projects, and other related trademarks.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] "WordPress is a factory that makes webpages" is a core analogy designed to clarify the functions of WordPress: it stores content and enables a user to create and publish webpages, requiring nothing beyond a domain and a hosting service.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress has a web template system using a template processor.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Its architecture is a front controller, routing all requests for non-static URIs to a single PHP file that parses the URI and identifies the target page.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] This allows support for more human-readable permalinks.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress users may install and switch among many different themes.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Themes allow users to change the look and functionality of a WordPress website without altering the core code or site content.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Custom code can be added to the website by using a child theme or through a code editor.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Every WordPress website requires at least one theme to be present.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Themes may be directly installed using the WordPress "Appearance" administration tool in the dashboard, or theme folders may be copied directly into the themes directory.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress themes are generally classified into two categories: free and premium.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Many free themes are listed in the WordPress theme directory (also known as the repository), and premium themes are available for purchase from marketplaces and individual WordPress developers.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress users may also create and develop their own custom themes and upload them in the WordPress directory or repository.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress' plugin architecture allows users to extend or depreciate the features and functionality of a website or blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As of December 2021, WordPress.org has 59,756 plugins available, each of which offers custom functions and features enabling users to tailor their sites to their specific needs.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] However, this does not include the available premium plugins (approximately 1,500+), which may not be listed in the WordPress.org repository.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] These customizations range from search engine optimization (SEO) to client portals used to display private information to logged-in users, to content management systems, to content displaying features, such as the addition of widgets and navigation bars.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Not all available plugins are always abreast with the upgrades, and as a result, they may not function properly or may not function at all.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] If the plugin developer has not tested the plugin with the last two major versions of WordPress, a warning message will be displayed on the plugin directory, informing users that the plugin may not work properly with the latest WordPress version.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Most plugins are available through WordPress themselves, either via downloading them and installing the files manually via FTP or through the WordPress dashboard.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] However, many third parties offer plugins through their websites, many of which are paid packages.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Web developers who wish to develop plugins need to learn WordPress' hook system, which consists of over 2,000 hooks (as of Version 5.7 in 2021) divided into two categories: action hooks and filter hooks.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Plugins also represent a development strategy that can transform WordPress into all sorts of software systems and applications, limited only by the imagination and creativity of programmers.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] These are implemented using custom plugins to create non-website systems, such as headless WordPress applications and Software as a Service (SaaS) products.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Plugins could also be used by hackers targeting sites that use WordPress, as hackers could exploit bugs in WordPress plugins instead of bugs in WordPress itself.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Phone apps for WordPress exist for Android, iOS.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] These applications, designed by Automattic, have options such as adding new blog posts and pages, commenting, moderating comments, replying to comments in addition to the ability to view the stats.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress also features integrated link management, a search engine–friendly, clean permalink structure; the ability to assign multiple categories to posts; and support for tagging of posts.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Automatic filters are also included, providing standardized formatting and styling of text in posts (for example, converting regular quotes to smart quotes).
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress also supports the trackback and pingback standards for displaying links to other sites that have themselves linked to a post or an article.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress posts can be edited in HTML, using the visual editor, or using one of several plugins that allow for a variety of customized editing features.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Before version 3, WordPress supported one blog per installation, although multiple concurrent copies may be run from different directories if configured to use separate database tables.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress Multisites (previously referred to as WordPress Multi-User, WordPress MU, or WPMU) was a fork of WordPress created to allow multiple blogs to exist within one installation but can be administered by a centralized maintainer.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress MU makes it possible for those with websites to host their own blogging communities, as well as control and moderate all the blogs from a single dashboard.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress MU adds eight new data tables for each blog.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As of the release of WordPress 3, WordPress MU has merged with WordPress.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As the development of b2/cafelog slowed down, Matt Mullenweg began pondering the idea of forking b2/cafelog and new features that he would want in a new CMS, in a blog post written on January 24, 2003.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Mike Little, a professional developer, became the first to comment on the blog post expressing interest to contribute.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The two worked together to create the first version of WordPress, version 0.70, which was released on May 27, 2003.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Christine Selleck Tremoulet, a friend of Mullenweg, suggested the name *WordPress*.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In 2004, the licensing terms for the competing Movable Type package were changed by Six Apart, resulting in many of its most influential users migrating to WordPress.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] By October 2009, the Open Source CMS MarketShare Report concluded that WordPress enjoyed the greatest brand strength of any open-source content management system.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As of December 2024, WordPress was used by 62.0% of all the websites whose content management system is known, and 22.52% of the top one million websites.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Starting September 2024, Mullenweg engaged WordPress, WordPress.com, and Automattic in a dispute leading to a lawsuit with hosting company WP Engine, causing widespread community concern.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Main releases of WordPress are codenamed after well-known jazz musicians, starting from version 1.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Although only the current release is officially supported, security updates are backported "as a courtesy" to all versions as far back as 4.0.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The December 2018 release of WordPress 5.0, "Bebo", is named in homage to the pioneering Cuban jazz musician Bebo Valdés.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] It included a new default editor "Gutenberg" – a block-based editor; that allows users to modify their displayed content in a much more user-friendly way than prior iterations.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Blocks are abstract units of markup that, composed together, form the content or layout of a web page.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Past content that was created on WordPress pages is listed under what is referred to as a Classic Block.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Before Gutenberg, there were several block-based editors available as WordPress plugins, e.g.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Following the release of Gutenberg, comparisons were made between it and those existing plugins.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The Classic Editor plugin was created as a result of User preferences and helped website developers maintain past plugins only compatible with WordPress 4.9, giving plugin developers time to get their plugins updated & compatible with the 5.0 release.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Having the Classic Editor plugin installed restores the "classic" editing experience that WordPress has had up until the WordPress 5.0 release.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The Classic Editor plugin will be supported at least until 2024.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As of August 2023, the Classic Editor plugin is active on over 5 million installations of WordPress.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Many security issues have been uncovered and patched in the software, particularly in 2007, 2008, and 2015.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] A cumulative list of WordPress security vulnerabilities, not all of which have been corrected in the version current at any time, is maintained by SecurityScorecard.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In January 2007, many high-profile search engine optimization (SEO) blogs, as well as many low-profile commercial blogs featuring AdSense, were targeted and attacked with a WordPress exploit.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] A separate vulnerability on one of the project site's web servers allowed an attacker to introduce exploitable code in the form of a back door to some downloads of WordPress 2.1.1.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The 2.1.2 release addressed this issue; an advisory released at the time advised all users to upgrade immediately.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In May 2007, a study revealed that 98% of WordPress blogs being run were exploitable because they were running outdated and unsupported versions of the software.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] To help mitigate this problem, WordPress made updating the software a much easier, "one-click" automated process in version 2.7 (released in December 2008).
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] However, the filesystem security settings required to enable the update process can be an additional risk.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In June 2013, it was found that some of the 50 most downloaded WordPress plugins were vulnerable to common Web attacks such as SQL injection and XSS.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] A separate inspection of the top 10 e-commerce plugins showed that seven of them were vulnerable.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] To promote better security and to streamline the update experience overall, automatic background updates were introduced in WordPress 3.7.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Individual installations of WordPress can be protected with security plugins that prevent user enumeration, hide resources, and thwart probes.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] It is especially important to keep WordPress plugins updated because would-be hackers can easily list all the plugins a site uses and then run scans searching for any vulnerabilities against those plugins.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] If vulnerabilities are found, they may be exploited to allow hackers to, for example, upload their files (such as a web shell) that collect sensitive information.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Developers can also use tools to analyze potential vulnerabilities, including Jetpack Protect, WPScan, WordPress Auditor, and WordPress Sploit Framework developed by 0pc0deFR.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] These types of tools research known vulnerabilities, such as CSRF, LFI, RFI, XSS, SQL injection, and user enumeration.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] However, not all vulnerabilities can be detected by tools, so it is advisable to check the code of plugins, themes, and other add-ins from other developers.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In March 2015, it was reported that the Yoast SEO plugin was vulnerable to SQL injection, allowing attackers to potentially execute arbitrary SQL commands.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The issue was fixed in version 1.7.4 of the plugin.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In January 2017, security auditors at Sucuri identified a vulnerability in the WordPress REST API that would allow any unauthenticated user to modify any post or page within a site running WordPress 4.7 or greater.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The auditors quietly notified WordPress developers, and within six days WordPress released a high-priority patch to version 4.7.2, which addressed the problem.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As of WordPress 6.0, the minimum PHP version requirement is PHP 5.6, which was released on August 28, 2014, and which has been unsupported by the PHP Group and not received any security patches since December 31, 2018.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Thus, WordPress recommends using PHP version 7.4 or greater.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In the absence of specific alterations to their default formatting code, WordPress-based websites use the canvas element to detect whether the browser can correctly render emoji.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Because Tor Browser does not currently discriminate between this legitimate use of the Canvas API and an effort to perform canvas fingerprinting, it warns that the website is attempting to 'extract HTML5 canvas image data.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Ongoing efforts seek workarounds to reassure privacy advocates while retaining the ability to check for proper emoji rendering capability.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Matt Mullenweg and Mike Little were co-founders of the project.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Current key people are listed on WordPress's Web site.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress is also developed by its community, including *WP tester*, a group of volunteers who test each release.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] They have early access to nightly builds, beta versions, and release candidates.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Errors are documented via a mailing list and the project's Trac tool.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Though largely developed by the community surrounding it, WordPress is closely associated with Automattic, the company founded by Matt Mullenweg.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress Foundation is a non-profit organization that was set up to support the WordPress project.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The purpose of the organization is to guarantee open access to WordPress's software projects forever.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] As part of this, the organization owns and manages WordPress, WordCamp, and related trademarks.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In January 2010, Matt Mullenweg formed the organization to own and manage the trademarks of WordPress project.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Previously – from 2006 onwards – Automattic acted as a short-term owner of the WordPress trademarks.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] From the beginning, he intended later to place the WordPress trademarks with the WordPress Foundation, which did not yet exist in 2006 and which eventually took longer to set up than expected.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] On December 14, 2021, Matt Mullenweg announced the WordPress Photo Directory at the State of the Word 2021 event.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] It is an open-source image directory for open images maintained by the WordPress project.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The image directory aims to provide an open alternative to closed image banks, such as Unsplash, Pixbaby, and Adobe Stock, whose licensing terms have become restrictive in recent years.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Use in WordPress themes, for example, is restricted.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In January 2022, the project began to gather volunteers, and in February, its own developer website was launched, where team representatives were next selected.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordCamps are casual, locally organized conferences covering everything related to WordPress.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The first such event was WordCamp 2006 in August 2006 in San Francisco, which lasted one day and had over 500 attendees.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The first WordCamp outside San Francisco was held in Beijing in September 2007.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Since then, there have been over 1,022 WordCamps in over 75 cities in 65 countries around the world.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordCamp San Francisco 2014 was the last official annual conference of WordPress developers and users taking place in San Francisco, having now been replaced with WordCamp US.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] First ran in 2013 as WordCamp Europe, regional WordCamps in other geographical regions are held to connect people who are not already active in their local communities and inspire attendees to start user communities in their hometowns.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] In 2019, the Nordic region had its own WordCamp Nordic.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] The first WordCamp Asia was to be held in 2020, but cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress' primary support website is WordPress.org.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] This support website hosts both WordPress Codex, the online manual for WordPress and a living repository for WordPress information and documentation, and WordPress Forums, an active online community of WordPress users.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] WordPress hosting services typically offer one-click WordPress installations, automated updates and backups, and security features to safeguard against common threats.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Many also provide support and are configured for optimal performance with the CMS.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] There are two primary types of WordPress hosting: shared WordPress hosting and managed WordPress hosting.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Shared WordPress hosting is a budget-friendly option where multiple websites reside on a single server, sharing resources.
[src:wordpress-cms/wordpress] Managed WordPress hosting includes comprehensive management of a WordPress site, including technical support, security, performance optimization, and often higher server resources, but comes at a higher price.
